I think that the problem warrants a fix in the real code, not in the test. `AddrManImpl::GetAddr_()` would try to overallocate if the caller passes > 100% which is meaningless. It already handles `max_addresses` properly: `nNodes = std::min(nNodes, max_addresses);`. If there are 1000 addresses and the caller asks for 5000, it would clamp it down to 1000.

<details>
<summary>[patch] clamp down the % of addresses, like already done for `max_addresses`</summary>

```diff
diff --git i/src/addrman.cpp w/src/addrman.cpp
index 43e7b6a32c..9fb092e9af 100644
--- i/src/addrman.cpp
+++ w/src/addrman.cpp
@@ -812,13 +812,13 @@ nid_type AddrManImpl::GetEntry(bool use_tried, size_t bucket, size_t position) c
 std::vector<CAddress> AddrManImpl::GetAddr_(size_t max_addresses, size_t max_pct, std::optional<Network> network, const bool filtered) const
 {
     AssertLockHeld(cs);
 
     size_t nNodes = vRandom.size();
     if (max_pct != 0) {
-        nNodes = max_pct * nNodes / 100;
+        nNodes = std::min(nNodes, max_pct * nNodes / 100);
     }
     if (max_addresses != 0) {
         nNodes = std::min(nNodes, max_addresses);
     }
 
     // gather a list of random nodes, skipping those of low quality
